[0.451, "o", "\u001b[3J\u001b[H\u001b[2J"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[1m# Your scanner found the CVEs. Now what do you actually run?\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[2.007, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1;32m$ trivy image --format json -o scan.json myapp:1.0   # (pre-recorded)\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[1.208, "o", "   8 vulnerabilities across 8 OS packages\r\n"]
[2.008, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1;32m$ remedify scan.json\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[1.359, "o", "# Remediation plan: `myapp:1.0`\r\n\r\n- **OS**: ubuntu 22.04\r\n- **Package manager**: apt\r\n- **Remediation steps**: 5 (covering 7 packages)\r\n- **No fix available**: 1 packages\r\n\r\n> 🏗️ **Container image** (immutable infra): the durable fix is to update the base image / package versions in your Dockerfile and **rebuild**, not to patch a running container in place. Use the commands below in the build (e.g. a `RUN` layer), then redeploy — running them in a live container is lost on the next restart.\r\n\r\n## libc-bin (+2 related packages)  `CRITICAL`\r\n\r\n- Packages: `libc-bin`, `libc6`, `libc6-dev` (same installed/fixed versions — updated together)\r\n- Installed: `2.35-0ubuntu3.6` -> Fix: `2.35-0ubuntu3.8`\r\n- CVEs: CVE-2023-6246, CVE-2024-33599, CVE-2024-33600\r\n- **Vendor backport (Ubuntu)**: the fixed version is a distro backport — it will not match the upstream version number. Scanners comparing against upstream may still flag it; trust the vendor advisory below.\r\n\r\n```bash\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "apt-get install --only-upgrade libc-bin=2.35-0ubuntu3.8 libc6=2.35-0ubuntu3.8 libc6-dev=2.35-0ubuntu3.8\r\n```\r\n- ⚠️ libc update: reboot strongly recommended (all processes link against it).\r\n\r\n## libssl3  `HIGH`\r\n\r\n- Installed: `3.0.2-0ubuntu1.15` -> Fix: `3.0.2-0ubuntu1.18`\r\n"]
[4.012, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1m# One command per source package — backports & reboots called out.\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[2.011, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1;32m$ remedify scan.json --format shell > fix.sh   &&   sudo bash fix.sh\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[1.213, "o", "   ...applied. rebuild / redeploy ... then re-scan → after.json\r\n"]
[2.013, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1m# Upgraded, re-scanned — but did it actually work?\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[2.010, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1;32m$ remedify --baseline scan.json after.json\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[1.256, "o", "# Remediation verification\r\n\r\n**myapp:1.0 → myapp:1.1** (ubuntu 22.04)\r\n\r\nFixed **5 / 7** fixable findings — **71%**. 2 remaining, 1 new, 1 unfixable (expected).\r\n\r\n> ⚠️ Comparing different targets — treat cross-target results as advisory.\r\n\r\n## ⛔ Still vulnerable (2) — action needed\r\n\r\n- **libssl3** `CVE-2024-6119` HIGH — upgraded but short of the fix: upgraded to 3.0.2-0ubuntu1.17 but need 3.0.2-0ubuntu1.18\r\n  - Vendor backport (Ubuntu): the fix version won't match the upstream number.\r\n- **linux-image-generic** `CVE-2024-26923` HIGH — untouched: still 5.15.0.105.102 (fix 5.15.0.107.104)\r\n\r\n## 🆕 New since baseline (1)\r\n\r\n- **libxml2** `CVE-2024-45491` HIGH\r\n\r\n## ✅ Resolved (5)\r\n\r\n"]
[4.012, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1m# Deterministic proof: what is fixed, what is still short, what is new.\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1m# pip install remedify  ·  github.com/higakikeita/remedify\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[3.011, "x", "0"]
